        <p class="prose-meta">Biography · Edmonton, Alberta, Canada</p>
        <h1>The longer story.</h1>
        <p class="deck">
          Consultant, writer, and AI policy critic working at the intersection of
          Technology, Governance, and Human Capital Development — across East Africa,
          Uganda, and Canada.
        </p>

        <h2>Where it started — Uganda</h2>
        <p>
          Born and raised in Uganda, the formative years came with a particular
          education: learning to read which systems worked and which ones didn't, who
          they served and who they quietly left out. That early lens became the
          foundation for everything that followed in Development, Technology, and
          Human Capital work across East Africa and now Canada.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img sm" data-label="Image placeholder — Kampala / Uganda roots" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <blockquote>
          "The gap between a well-funded programme and a working one is almost
          always a human capital and systems problem — not a resource problem."
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Development Sector —
          <a href="https://watoto.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Watoto</a>,
          <a href="https://www.pedaids.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">EGPAF</a>,
          <a href="https://www.ghcorps.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Global Health Corps</a>
        </h2>
        <p>
          A decade of field-level work across East Africa's most significant Development
          and Health organisations sharpened the diagnostic instinct and deepened the
          commitment to the people implementing policy, not just writing it. At EGPAF,
          health programme delivery at scale meant learning where reporting systems broke
          down and where frontline health workers were working around broken ICT tools
          instead of with them.
        </p>
        <p>
          Global Health Corps brought a fellowship experience that cross-pollinated
          leadership thinking from across Africa and the Global South.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img" data-label="Image placeholder — development sector / East Africa field work" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <h2>Technology Sector —
          <a href="https://medic.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Medic</a>,
          LMH,
          Guild Digital Uganda,
          <a href="https://www.amii.ca" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Amii</a>
        </h2>
        <p>
          The Technology chapter deepened through engagements that moved progressively
          closer to building. Information systems management at Watoto and LMH (Lubaga
          Mission Hospital) provided the NGO-sector ICT foundation.
        </p>
        <p>
          The most substantive technology work came through <strong>Guild Digital Uganda</strong>
          — a registered nonprofit Technology company with seven staff and three years of
          sustained operation. The flagship product was <strong>rCHMIS</strong>, a refugee
          Community Health Management Information System integrated with Uganda's
          <a href="https://www.health.go.ug" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ministry of Health</a>.
          rCHMIS served more than 780,000 refugees, achieving an 83% adoption rate among
          frontline health workers, and extended into Rwanda under a Memorandum of
          Understanding. $50K+ in grants secured; $30K+ in contracts delivered.
        </p>
        <p>
          More recently, engagement with <strong>Amii</strong> — the Alberta Machine
          Intelligence Institute — has connected the AI and Machine Learning ecosystem in
          Edmonton with the Policy and Governance work now central to Olympia &amp; Associates.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img" data-label="Image placeholder — rCHMIS / Guild Digital Uganda / Technology work" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <blockquote>
          "Careful ICT systems beat clever ones at scale. The health workers adopting
          rCHMIS weren't adopting technology — they were adopting a tool that finally
          made their job easier."
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Human Capital Development —
          Kampala Leadership Hub,
          <a href="https://olympia-associates.ca" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Olympia &amp; Associates</a>
        </h2>
        <p>
          The Human Capital chapter formalised in 2018 with the founding of the
          <strong>Kampala Leadership Hub (KLH)</strong> in Kampala — a management
          consulting practice that delivered career coaching and a full management course
          for young team leaders and small business owners.
        </p>
        <p>
          After relocating to Edmonton, Alberta, Olympia &amp; Associates was established
          as a registered Alberta technology and business consulting practice — five streams,
          one through-line: does this actually reach the person it was designed for? The
          streams span High School Career Consulting, Professional Development, Leadership
          &amp; Business Consulting, AI Policy &amp; Governance, and Newcomer &amp;
          Immigration Pathways.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img sm" data-label="Image placeholder — Edmonton / Olympia & Associates" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <h2>The current work</h2>
        <p>
          Current engagements include a completed digital presence build for
          <strong>Janzen Family Care</strong> in Edmonton and a drafted AI Policy review
          for the <strong><a href="https://www.unoc.go.ug" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Uganda National Oil Company (UNOC)</a></strong>.
          A critical response to a Ugandan private university vice chancellor's AI
          commentary went viral on LinkedIn in early 2026, re-establishing a public voice
          in the AI Literacy and Governance conversation across the diaspora.
        </p>
        <p>
          A PhD path is in development, focused on LLM adoption in nonprofits and
          non-traditional users, targeting the University of Alberta. Brian can be
          reached on <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/bssennoga" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>
          for general conversation, and through
          <a href="https://olympia-associates.ca" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Olympia &amp; Associates</a>
          for consulting engagements.
        </p>

